    <p><a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a></p>

    <h1>Se&#xAD;cu&#xAD;rity forces on high alert as In&#xAD;au&#xAD;gu&#xAD;ra&#xAD;tion Day draws near</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <time datetime="2021-01-12"><a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20210112/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2021-01-12">2021-01-12</a></time> -
        

            <a href="/category/tag-268452461/en/sg">Crime</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-268436357/en/sg">U.S. News</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-268490687/en/sg">Politics</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537286254/en/sg">Washington</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537068240/en/sg">United States of America</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537074572/en/sg">Joe Biden</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537201501/en/sg">Muriel Bowser</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537074648/en/sg">Department of Homeland Security</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537528215/en/sg">Homeland</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537215160/en/sg">Roy Blunt</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537069217/en/sg">Donald Trump</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-536937327/en/sg">Congress of the United States</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537543248/en/sg">Capitol Hill</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537070522/en/sg">Iowa</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537070516/en/sg">Florida</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-539249773/en/sg">United States Army</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-541262738/en/sg">United States Department of Justice</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-540248051/en/sg">United States Department of Defense</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-536895947/en/sg">Pentagon</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537068829/en/sg">Perm</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-538623969/en/sg">Molotov</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537155968/en/sg">US Military Academy</a>     </section>

        <p>WASH­ING­TON • Fed­eral and lo­cal au­thor­i­ties across the United States pressed their hunt over the weekend for mem­bers of the an­gry mob that stormed the Capi­tol build­ing last Wed­nes­day, as Wash­ing­ton’s mayor is­sued an ur­gent ap­peal to start pre­par­ing im­me­di­ately for more po­ten­tial vi­o­lence be­fore, dur­ing and af­ter the in­au­gu­ra­tion of Pres­i­dent-elect Joe Bi­den.</p>
        <p>Fol­low­ing one of the most stun­ning se­cu­rity lapses in the city’s his­tory, Mayor Muriel Bowser sent a firmly worded let­ter last Satur­day to the Depart­ment of Home­land Se­cu­rity, ask­ing of­fi­cials to start the im­ple­men­ta­tion of height­ened se­cu­rity mea­sures yes­ter­day. This was oth­er­wise set to be­gin on Jan 19, a day be­fore Mr Bi­den’s swear­ing-in.</p>
        <p>Ms Bowser’s call to ac­tion was echoed on Sun­day by Sen­a­tor Roy Blunt, who is charged with over­see­ing the plan­ning of the in­au­gu­ral cel­e­bra­tion.</p>
        <p>The Capi­tol com­plex, typ­i­cally a hive of ac­tiv­ity, re­mained cut off from its sur­round­ings on Sun­day night by troop de­ploy­ments and an im­pos­ing scrim of over 2m-tall, un­scal­able fenc­ing.</p>
        <p>Still in shock from the worst breach of the build­ing in more than two cen­turies, law­mak­ers were ex­pected to turn their at­ten­tion this week to a sec­ond slate of im­peach­ment charges against Pres­i­dent Don­ald Trump, who has said lit­tle about the ri­ots he helped in­cite.</p>
        <p>Se­cu­rity ex­perts warned over the weekend that some far-right ex­trem­ist groups have now started to fo­cus at­ten­tion on In­au­gu­ra­tion Day and are al­ready dis­cussing an as­sault sim­i­lar to the one on the Capi­tol, which led to the sack­ing of con­gres­sional of­fices and the deaths of at least five peo­ple, in­clud­ing a Capi­tol Po­lice of­fi­cer.</p>
        <p>As at Sun­day, nearly 400 peo­ple had joined a pri­vate group on­line ded­i­cated to what is be­ing billed as the “Mil­lion Mili­tia March”, an event sched­uled to take place in Wash­ing­ton on Jan 20.</p>
        <p>While most of the chat­ter on­line ap­pears to be di­rected towards In­au­gu­ra­tion Day, some on the right have ar­gued that pro-Trump ac­tivists should in­stead gather once again on Capi­tol Hill and hold other ral­lies in cities out­side Wash­ing­ton on Sun­day.</p>
        <p>Armed with fed­eral war­rants, law en­force­ment of­fi­cers spent much of the weekend crack­ing down on mem­bers of the mob in Wash­ing­ton, mak­ing a se­ries of ar­rests in states from Iowa to Florida, and fil­ing new charges against some of the more than 80 peo­ple who were taken into cus­tody last week by of­fi­cers in Wash­ing­ton.</p>
        <p>At least 25 do­mes­tic ter­ror­ism cases have been opened as a re­sult of last Wed­nes­day’s deadly as­sault on the Capi­tol, US Army Sec­re­tary Ryan Mc­Carthy told a Demo­cratic law­maker on Sun­day.</p>
        <p>The Jus­tice Depart­ment also said two more men were ar­rested in con­nec­tion with the ri­ot­ing.</p>
        <p>Rep­re­sen­ta­tive Ja­son Crow, a mem­ber of the House of Rep­re­sen­ta­tives Armed Ser­vices Com­mit­tee, said Mr Mc­Carthy told him the Pen­tagon was aware of “fur­ther pos­si­ble threats posed by wouldbe ter­ror­ists” in the days lead­ing up to and in­clud­ing Mr Bi­den’s in­au­gu­ra­tion on Jan 20.</p>
        <p>“Long guns, Molo­tov cock­tails, ex­plo­sive de­vices and zip ties were re­cov­ered, which sug­gests a greater dis­as­ter was nar­rowly averted,” Mr Crow, a for­mer Army Ranger, said in a sum­mary of his call with Mr Mc­Carthy.</p>
        <p>Mr Mc­Carthy as­sured him the Pen­tagon was work­ing with lo­cal and fed­eral law en­force­ment to co­or­di­nate se­cu­rity prepa­ra­tions af­ter what he de­scribed as “de­fi­cient law en­force­ment threat re­port­ing” be­fore the as­sault last Wed­nes­day.</p>


</article>

